261
00:10:07,775 --> 00:10:09,076
Well, congratulations.

262
00:10:09,142 --> 00:10:10,844
You're the first person
to cheer him up all summer.

263
00:10:10,911 --> 00:10:12,680
You win.
Oh, what do I win?

264
00:10:12,746 --> 00:10:13,881
I'll tell you what you win:

265
00:10:13,947 --> 00:10:15,415
I'm taking you away
this weekend.

266
00:10:15,482 --> 00:10:16,416
You are?
Mmm.

267
00:10:16,483 --> 00:10:17,584
That's so nice.

268
00:10:17,651 --> 00:10:18,919
Yeah, my aunt and uncle
have a beach house

269
00:10:18,986 --> 00:10:20,788
out in Montauk, oh,
it's really romantic.

270
00:10:20,854 --> 00:10:22,923
My uncle's had like
three affairs there.

271
00:10:22,990 --> 00:10:24,792
Wow, must be a nice house,

272
00:10:24,858 --> 00:10:26,626
I've seen pictures
of your uncle.

273
00:10:26,694 --> 00:10:29,062
This is going
to be so great.

274
00:10:29,129 --> 00:10:30,964
We'll finally get
some time alone.

275
00:10:31,031 --> 00:10:33,667
Are you sure Marshall's
going to be okay with this?

276
00:10:33,734 --> 00:10:35,035
Yeah, absolutely.

277
00:10:35,102 --> 00:10:37,137
Dude, I'm doing much better.
Oh.

278
00:10:37,204 --> 00:10:38,672
In fact, take my car.

279
00:10:38,739 --> 00:10:39,707
Really?
Yeah.

280
00:10:39,773 --> 00:10:41,374
Hey, thanks...
and, hey,

281
00:10:41,441 --> 00:10:43,576
if you need anything day
or night, just call me--

282
00:10:43,643 --> 00:10:46,179
You know what,
please don't call me.

283
00:10:46,246 --> 00:10:48,048
What? What's wrong?

284
00:10:48,115 --> 00:10:50,517
It's, uh,
Lily's credit card bill.

285
00:10:50,583 --> 00:10:51,719
She must have forgotten

286
00:10:51,785 --> 00:10:52,986
to switch her address.

287
00:10:53,053 --> 00:10:54,154
So?

288
00:10:54,221 --> 00:10:56,123
So, I wonder what kind
of charges she's making

289
00:10:56,189 --> 00:10:57,590
out there in San Francisco.
No.

290
00:10:57,657 --> 00:10:59,326
No, no good can come
from looking at this.

291
00:10:59,392 --> 00:11:00,794
You've made too much
progress already.

292
00:11:00,861 --> 00:11:02,996
I know but I just,
maybe the--
No!

293
00:11:03,063 --> 00:11:05,365
You're going to
thank me for this.

294
00:11:07,835 --> 00:11:10,871
You're a good friend, Ted.

295
00:11:11,839 --> 00:11:14,274
August 5th,
one charge-- tickets.

296
00:11:14,341 --> 00:11:18,278
To what? George Clinton
and the P-Funk All-Stars.

297
00:11:18,345 --> 00:11:21,481
August 10th, one charge:
Tennis Emporium.

298
00:11:21,548 --> 00:11:24,217
August 18th, two charges:

299
00:11:24,284 --> 00:11:28,889
Mario's Bistro
and, get this, Pet Palace.

300
00:11:29,890 --> 00:11:31,892
You guys see what
this means, right?

301
00:11:34,527 --> 00:11:36,964
Wow, Mario's Bistro.

302
00:11:37,030 --> 00:11:39,833
What a perfect place
to whore around.

303
00:11:39,900 --> 00:11:42,569
Only the best
for my little Lily pad.

304
00:11:42,635 --> 00:11:45,172
Oh, funk legend
George Clinton,

305
00:11:45,238 --> 00:11:47,908
I am so glad you spotted
me at your concert

306
00:11:47,975 --> 00:11:52,145
and dragged me onstage to dance
with you Courtney Cox-style.

307
00:11:52,212 --> 00:11:54,314
And I'm so glad you agreed
to play tennis with me.

308
00:11:54,381 --> 00:11:55,515
Aw.

309
00:11:55,582 --> 00:11:56,884
You know, Marshall
tried to get me

310
00:11:56,950 --> 00:11:58,919
to play tennis
for nine years,

311
00:11:58,986 --> 00:12:03,490
but I didn't do it, because
I never truly loved him.

312
00:12:03,556 --> 00:12:05,058
I got you a gift.

313
00:12:05,125 --> 00:12:06,326
Oh.

314
00:12:07,427 --> 00:12:08,929
A ferret.

315
00:12:08,996 --> 00:12:12,766
Oh, I'll buy it some food
next door at the Pet Palace.

316
00:12:12,833 --> 00:12:15,168
Oh, I've always wanted one,

317
00:12:15,235 --> 00:12:18,338
but Marshall had this
secret phobia of ferrets.

318
00:12:18,405 --> 00:12:21,274
I bet that's something he made
you promise not to tell nobody.

319
00:12:21,341 --> 00:12:23,476
(laughing):
It was.

320
00:12:23,543 --> 00:12:24,912
Oh.

321
00:12:24,978 --> 00:12:27,547
I love you, funk
legend George Clinton.

322
00:12:27,614 --> 00:12:29,749
I love you, too, Lily.

323
00:12:29,817 --> 00:12:31,418
That's right, Marshall,
she's all mine.

324
00:12:31,484 --> 00:12:33,720
Now I'm gonna let her play
with my hair.

325
00:12:33,787 --> 00:12:35,722
* Ow, we want the funk *

326
00:12:35,789 --> 00:12:38,258
* Give up the funk... *

327
00:12:38,325 --> 00:12:39,592
That's the craziest
thing I've ever heard.

328
00:12:39,659 --> 00:12:41,261
Yeah, why are you
afraid of ferrets?

329
00:12:41,328 --> 00:12:42,495
They're adorable.

330
00:12:42,562 --> 00:12:45,398
Because, Robin, they're like
fuzzy, tube-shaped rats.

331
00:12:46,566 --> 00:12:48,101
Plus, those charges are
from, like, a month ago.

332
00:12:48,168 --> 00:12:49,302
Exactly.
For new charges,

333
00:12:49,369 --> 00:12:50,971
you have to go
to her online account.

334
00:12:51,038 --> 00:12:55,242
You can see credit card activity
from, like, two hours ago.

335
00:12:56,076 --> 00:12:59,012
But, you know, don't.

336
00:12:59,880 --> 00:13:01,681
Why do you talk?

337
00:13:01,748 --> 00:13:03,783
Why do you talk?!

338
00:13:03,851 --> 00:13:04,952
BARNEY:
He needs her password.

339
00:13:05,018 --> 00:13:06,186
It's not like he
has her password.

340
00:13:06,253 --> 00:13:08,421
Ooh, this is good,
he has her password.

341
00:13:08,488 --> 00:13:10,690
There's a charge
from earlier today:

342
00:13:10,757 --> 00:13:12,792
the Kellett Hotel on 5th.

343
00:13:13,693 --> 00:13:14,928
I don't believe this.

344
00:13:14,995 --> 00:13:17,064
Lily's back in New York.

345
00:13:21,201 --> 00:13:22,870
I can't believe this.

346
00:13:22,936 --> 00:13:24,504
Lily's in New York?

347
00:13:24,571 --> 00:13:25,906
I-I guess I've been thinking

348
00:13:25,973 --> 00:13:27,340
when she got back,
she'd call me.

349
00:13:27,407 --> 00:13:29,409
That's really
the only reason

350
00:13:29,476 --> 00:13:31,644
I've been able to hold it
together so far this summer.

351
00:13:31,711 --> 00:13:34,014
This has been "holding
it together"?

352
00:13:34,081 --> 00:13:36,049
Okay, you know what?
I'm calling her.

353
00:13:36,116 --> 00:13:37,350
No.
Ted, give me the phone.

354
00:13:37,417 --> 00:13:38,718
You're not calling her,
this changes nothing.

355
00:13:38,785 --> 00:13:41,388
You, come here.

356
00:13:41,454 --> 00:13:43,156
Look, while we're away
this weekend, can you keep

357
00:13:43,223 --> 00:13:45,158
an eye on him, make sure
he doesn't call that hotel?

358
00:13:45,225 --> 00:13:46,626
You want me to babysit him?

359
00:13:46,693 --> 00:13:48,161
(laughs)
20 bucks.

360
00:13:48,228 --> 00:13:49,496
An hour.

361
00:13:49,562 --> 00:13:50,430
And money for pizza.

362
00:13:50,497 --> 00:13:52,199
Uh, yeah, how about
you do it for free

363
00:13:52,265 --> 00:13:54,334
or every time we hang out,
you have to watch this?

364
00:13:54,401 --> 00:13:55,802
Come here.
Ooh.

365
00:13:55,869 --> 00:13:59,072
My little blue-eyed
baby, baby lips.
Ooh, ooh, sugar, sugar...

366
00:13:59,139 --> 00:14:00,373
Okay, I'll do it!

367
00:14:00,440 --> 00:14:01,541
Stop being a couple.

368
00:14:02,609 --> 00:14:04,544
Marshall.
Marshall, Marshall!

369
00:14:04,611 --> 00:14:06,313
Ted, I know I shouldn't
do this, but I have to!
You call her

370
00:14:06,379 --> 00:14:07,881
We were together for
nine years!
and everything
we've been working so hard for

371
00:14:07,948 --> 00:14:09,782
is completely flushed
down the toi...

372
00:14:09,849 --> 00:14:11,284
Hello, Lily Aldrin's
room, please.

373
00:14:12,252 --> 00:14:13,987
Thank you.
Hang up now.

374
00:14:14,054 --> 00:14:15,722
Ted, I can't hang up now.
Hang up now.

375
00:14:15,788 --> 00:14:17,490
The missiles are in the air, and
I know that you don't approve.

376
00:14:17,557 --> 00:14:18,858
Hang up.
Hello.

377
00:14:24,998 --> 00:14:26,233
Uh, a guy answered.

378
00:14:27,400 --> 00:14:29,069
There's-there's a guy
in her room.

379
00:14:30,703 --> 00:14:31,871
I'm going down there.

380
00:14:31,939 --> 00:14:32,940
BARNEY:
Dude, you can't do that.

381
00:14:33,006 --> 00:14:34,507
I have to go down there,
and I have

382
00:14:34,574 --> 00:14:36,476
to tell her I love her; I have
to beg her to take me back,

383
00:14:36,543 --> 00:14:38,311
even if I have to
get down on my knees.

384
00:14:38,378 --> 00:14:39,947
Marshall, you
can't do that.
Oh, really, why not?

385
00:14:40,013 --> 00:14:41,614
TED:
56 days.

386
00:14:41,681 --> 00:14:44,551
That's how long it took me
to get right about here.

387
00:14:44,617 --> 00:14:46,219
Because you're pathetic!

388
00:14:48,255 --> 00:14:50,924
I'm sorry, but right now,
you are not Marshall.

389
00:14:50,991 --> 00:14:52,159
You are the miserable,

390
00:14:52,225 --> 00:14:55,996
whining, shampoo-sniffing
ghost of Marshall,

391
00:14:56,063 --> 00:14:57,364
and frankly, a guy like you

392
00:14:57,430 --> 00:14:59,366
doesn't have a shot
in hell with a girl like Lily.

393
00:14:59,432 --> 00:15:01,001
You know
who might have a shot

394
00:15:01,068 --> 00:15:02,802
somewhere down the line?

395
00:15:02,869 --> 00:15:03,803
Marshall.

396
00:15:03,870 --> 00:15:05,405
The real Marshall.

397
00:15:05,472 --> 00:15:07,774
But if you go down there right
now like this, you're going

398
00:15:07,840 --> 00:15:10,077
to blow it for him, and he's
never going to forgive you.

399
00:15:11,044 --> 00:15:12,179
Of course, whatever I say,

400
00:15:12,245 --> 00:15:13,713
you're just going to do
the opposite,

401
00:15:13,780 --> 00:15:14,747
so have a great weekend.

402
00:15:14,814 --> 00:15:15,915
Good luck screwing up
your life.

403
00:15:15,983 --> 00:15:17,550
Come on, Robin.

404
00:15:18,618 --> 00:15:19,619
(clears throat)

405
00:15:21,588 --> 00:15:23,656
Is it still okay if
we borrow the car?

406
00:15:25,358 --> 00:15:28,395
Bold. Bold to go for the car.

407
00:15:31,631 --> 00:15:32,865
What?

408
00:15:32,932 --> 00:15:35,135
I didn't say a thing.

409
00:15:35,202 --> 00:15:36,903
You think I was
too hard on him.

410
00:15:36,970 --> 00:15:38,438
I didn't say a thing.
(scoffs)

411
00:15:38,505 --> 00:15:40,507
I can't believe you're accusing
me of being too hard on him.

412
00:15:40,573 --> 00:15:42,242
You're the one
who said "tough love."

413
00:15:42,309 --> 00:15:44,677
Yeah, tough love, not
"hand the guy a noose."

414
00:15:44,744 --> 00:15:46,713
Oh, but it's okay
to hand him a nine millimeter?

415
00:15:46,779 --> 00:15:49,649
Yeah, he told me.

416
00:15:51,985 --> 00:15:53,486
So you're a gun nut?

417
00:15:53,553 --> 00:15:57,090
No, I'm a gun enthusiast.
Do you know
how many people

418
00:15:57,157 --> 00:15:58,391
are killed each year
The Second Amendment

419
00:15:58,458 --> 00:15:59,326
protects my right
to bear arms...
in accidents...

420
00:15:59,392 --> 00:16:01,194
All right, all
right, all right.

421
00:16:01,261 --> 00:16:03,463
I was too hard on him.

422
00:16:03,530 --> 00:16:05,432
A little.

423
00:16:05,498 --> 00:16:06,633
(laughs softly)

424
00:16:06,699 --> 00:16:10,637
I'm going to call Barney,
see how they're doing.

425
00:16:10,703 --> 00:16:12,205
(phone rings)
Go for Barney.

426
00:16:12,272 --> 00:16:13,306
Oh, hey, where are you guys?

427
00:16:13,373 --> 00:16:14,807
We're at a fundraiser,

428
00:16:14,874 --> 00:16:17,044
helping young women raise money
for community college.

429
00:16:17,110 --> 00:16:18,078
Strip club, nice.

430
00:16:18,145 --> 00:16:20,113
Is Marshall okay?
(laughs)

431
00:16:20,180 --> 00:16:21,614
Yeah, he's here
and he's great.

432
00:16:21,681 --> 00:16:22,615
Uh, hang on.
Marshall?

433
00:16:22,682 --> 00:16:24,351
Tell Ted that--

434
00:16:24,417 --> 00:16:25,985
Uh-oh.

435
00:16:26,053 --> 00:16:28,488
Already?

436
00:16:28,555 --> 00:16:29,756
What? What uh-oh?

437
00:16:29,822 --> 00:16:30,923
He's gone.

438
00:16:30,990 --> 00:16:31,958
You lost him?

439
00:16:32,025 --> 00:16:33,126
I can't believe this.

440
00:16:33,193 --> 00:16:34,294
He's going to go down
to that hotel.

441
00:16:34,361 --> 00:16:35,662
Crap, you're right.

442
00:16:35,728 --> 00:16:37,064
Okay, okay, here's the plan,
here's the plan.

443
00:16:37,130 --> 00:16:38,531
You go down to the hotel
and find him.

444
00:16:38,598 --> 00:16:39,932
I'll stay here
and get a lap dance.

445
00:16:39,999 --> 00:16:40,867
On three. One, two...

446
00:16:40,933 --> 00:16:42,069
Barney!

447
00:16:47,207 --> 00:16:49,642
Was there a hot tub
at your uncle's place?

448
00:16:49,709 --> 00:16:52,179
A really nice one.

449
00:16:55,448 --> 00:16:58,351
Hi, uh, could you tell me
what room Lily Aldrin's in?

450
00:16:59,852 --> 00:17:01,554
Marshall.

451
00:17:01,621 --> 00:17:03,490
(chuckling):
Hey.

452
00:17:04,557 --> 00:17:05,992
What happened?

453
00:17:06,059 --> 00:17:08,761
Well, I went
up to Lily's floor,

454
00:17:08,828 --> 00:17:11,364
and I had this little speech
in my head--

455
00:17:11,431 --> 00:17:13,266
everything I've been wanting
to say to her all summer

456
00:17:13,333 --> 00:17:17,003
about love, loyalty, respect.

457
00:17:17,070 --> 00:17:20,240
I knocked on the door.

458
00:17:24,644 --> 00:17:27,480
So you knocked out
Lily's new boyfriend?

459
00:17:27,547 --> 00:17:28,415
Yeah.

460
00:17:28,481 --> 00:17:29,849
It wasn't Lily's boyfriend.

461
00:17:29,916 --> 00:17:31,551
What? Who-- who was it?

462
00:17:31,618 --> 00:17:34,354
TED:
His name was Joey Adalian,
although he went by a number

463
00:17:34,421 --> 00:17:37,157
of aliases in his years
as an identity thief.

464
00:17:37,224 --> 00:17:38,791
Apparently,
earlier in the summer...

465
00:17:41,027 --> 00:17:42,562
LILY:
Oh, this is so embarrassing.

466
00:17:42,629 --> 00:17:44,964
I-I could have sworn
I had some change.

467
00:17:45,031 --> 00:17:46,899
I know, I know.

468
00:17:46,966 --> 00:17:48,067
I'm sorry.

469
00:17:48,135 --> 00:17:50,903
Oh, here we go.

470
00:17:50,970 --> 00:17:52,539
No, that's-that's a button.

471
00:17:52,605 --> 00:17:54,441
It was a button.

472
00:17:57,144 --> 00:17:59,078
Do you, uh, take
credit cards?

473
00:17:59,146 --> 00:18:01,047
Yes, I do.

474
00:18:01,114 --> 00:18:03,216
So Lily's not back in town,

475
00:18:03,283 --> 00:18:04,284
and she doesn't
have a boyfriend?

476
00:18:04,351 --> 00:18:05,685
Th-That's good news, right?

477
00:18:05,752 --> 00:18:07,554
Yeah.

478
00:18:07,620 --> 00:18:09,989
I don't know.

479
00:18:10,056 --> 00:18:11,291
Those credit card charges

480
00:18:11,358 --> 00:18:13,560
were the only remaining
connection I had to her.

481
00:18:15,027 --> 00:18:17,897
I don't know where she is
or what she's doing.

482
00:18:17,964 --> 00:18:22,302
She was my whole life, man,
and now she's-she's gone.

483
00:18:26,573 --> 00:18:29,609
You know, first day of
college, I showed up,

484
00:18:29,676 --> 00:18:30,810
I was so freaked out,

485
00:18:30,877 --> 00:18:35,815
and-and I got up to my room,
and there was my roommate,

486
00:18:35,882 --> 00:18:38,151
lying on the bed with
his feet up on the wall.

487
00:18:38,218 --> 00:18:40,853
Had headphones on,
big smile on his face

488
00:18:40,920 --> 00:18:42,355
like he just didn't give a crap.

489
00:18:43,723 --> 00:18:44,624
Happy.

490
00:18:44,691 --> 00:18:46,726
Confident.
Not afraid of anything.

491
00:18:47,760 --> 00:18:50,230
That guy was you.

492
00:18:50,297 --> 00:18:51,864
You before you met Lily.

493
00:18:53,933 --> 00:18:55,668
Ted?

494
00:18:55,735 --> 00:18:56,769
Yeah?

495
00:18:56,836 --> 00:18:58,738
I was high that day.

496
00:18:58,805 --> 00:19:00,173
I was.

497
00:19:00,240 --> 00:19:02,509
I was so high,
I thought you were the dean.

498
00:19:04,411 --> 00:19:06,246
Wh-What I'm saying is

499
00:19:06,313 --> 00:19:08,948
there's a version of
you without Lily,

500
00:19:09,015 --> 00:19:11,518
and it's not this.

501
00:19:11,584 --> 00:19:14,487
You can't let Lily
steal your identity

502
00:19:14,554 --> 00:19:17,257
the way that guy stole hers.

503
00:19:19,826 --> 00:19:20,793
Okay.

504
00:19:21,961 --> 00:19:24,597
Okay, resolved.

505
00:19:24,664 --> 00:19:27,200
Starting tomorrow, I'm
going to start being okay.

506
00:19:27,267 --> 00:19:28,701
(chuckles)

507
00:19:28,768 --> 00:19:29,902
Cheers.
Cheers.

508
00:19:31,938 --> 00:19:34,907
* *

509
00:19:36,509 --> 00:19:38,411
But he wasn't,

510
00:19:38,478 --> 00:19:40,647
'cause that's not
how life works.

511
00:19:40,713 --> 00:19:43,416
The next day, he found one
of her socks or something,

512
00:19:43,483 --> 00:19:45,818
and we were back to square one.

513
00:19:47,920 --> 00:19:49,556
And then, one morning...

514
00:19:49,622 --> 00:19:53,125
Ted, I think
you should see this.

515
00:19:53,192 --> 00:19:54,294
Oh, no, what now?

516
00:19:56,263 --> 00:19:59,366
Marshall,
what are you doing?

517
00:19:59,432 --> 00:20:00,733
It's Sunday.

518
00:20:00,800 --> 00:20:02,802
It's pancakes day.

519
00:20:07,940 --> 00:20:09,342
It took him 67 days

520
00:20:09,409 --> 00:20:13,546
and one really disgusting
batch of pancakes...

521
00:20:16,883 --> 00:20:17,984
So good.

522
00:20:18,050 --> 00:20:20,687
Mmm.
So good.

523
00:20:20,753 --> 00:20:23,590
...but Marshall had come back
from the dead.

524
00:20:23,656 --> 00:20:26,559
Because while baseball,
strippers, and guns can help,

525
00:20:26,626 --> 00:20:30,129
the only thing that can really
heal a broken heart is time.

526
00:20:30,196 --> 00:20:33,165
* I try to laugh about it *

527
00:20:33,232 --> 00:20:37,604
* Cover it all up with lies *

528
00:20:37,670 --> 00:20:41,374
* I try to laugh about it *

529
00:20:41,441 --> 00:20:44,344
* Hiding the tears
from my eyes *

530
00:20:44,411 --> 00:20:51,318
* 'Cause boys don't cry. *

